o not do so in a uniform, homogeneous, or predictable manner. At the same time, public understandings and expectations of security and citizenship themselves shape how developments in anti-terrorism frameworks are discussed and evaluated. This important new book will be of interest to researchers and students working in a wide range of disciplines including Political Science, International Relations, Security Studies and Sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenshipzGreat Britain. 0aNational securityzGreat Britain. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aTerrorismxPreventionzGreat Britain. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh  aAnti-Terrorism.  aCitizenship.  aCommunity Cohesion.  aCounter Terrorism.  aEveryday Security.  aIdentity.  aParticipation.  aRights.  aSecurity.  aVernacular Security.1 aJarvis, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLister, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLister, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499154840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784991548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784991548/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles